Linear combinations au + bv form the plane A
through the origin. Adding vector p to each
point on that plane gives the parallel plane B
consisting of all vectors of the form
p + au + bv. This plane passes through p
considered as a point rather than a vector.

Multiples av of the vector v form the line A
through the origin. Adding vector p to each
point on that line gives the parallel line B
consisting of all vectors of the form p + av.
This line passes through p considered as
a point rather than a vector.
